Apple’s iPhones are often seen as secure, but they have important downsides. The system is closed, meaning users and researchers can't fully inspect what’s happening under the surface. iCloud data is only partially end-to-end encrypted, and backups are often accessible to Apple or law enforcement. Powerful spyware like Pegasus has shown that iPhones can be hacked without user interaction. The App Store, while curated, isn’t immune to malicious apps and blocks alternative security tools like firewalls or system monitors. Apple's reliance on the Apple ID makes it a single point of failure.

Still, iPhones have a few strong security features. All devices come with full-disk encryption by default. The Secure Enclave stores sensitive data like Face ID and encryption keys in a protected chip. Apple also provides years of fast, global software updates, which helps keep devices patched. Apps are sandboxed, which limits their ability to affect the system or other apps. Overall, iPhones offer good basic security for the average user, but power users may find the lack of control and transparency a serious downside
